{
  "texts": [
    "Thus, [D 1, D] = D 2, and since the left-hand-side is symmetric, we have [D 1, D] = 0.",
    "In particular, D is invertible (its symmetric part D is positive definite).Regarding the zeroes of X, we first notice that D is invertible, as it is a normal operator with positivedefinite self-adjoint part.",
    "We work in exponential coordinates.",
    "Using the Baker-Campbell-Hausdorff formula and nilpotency, it is easy to see that a right-invariant vector field Y R whose value at e is Y ∈ 𝔫 is represented in these coordinates by a map 𝔫 ∋ U → F (U):= P (adU)Y, where P is a polynomial whose constant coefficient is 1.",
    "Finding a zero for X = X D + Y R is thus equivalent to proving that the map (37) DU + F (U) = 0 always has a solution on 𝔫."
  ]
}